Security Operations Fundamentals > [T2]: Ticketing Systems for Incident Response

Ticketing Systems  

Incident Response is a methodological approach, and because of that, defenders need to be able to follow the pre-defined IR process and repeat it whenever required. Ticketing systems are what defenders use to achieve this goal. These systems provide many helpful functions, such as organizing a high volume of alerts and notifications, tracking and prioritizing incidents, and improving communication between the involved parties. 

Ticketing systems can be standalone software such as ServiceDesk and ServiceNow or can be offered as a component of an Incident management platform. Selecting which option works best for your organization depends on the organization's business needs and requirements. Since ticketing systems can be considered a central repo for all incident details, they can usually integrate with other SOC security solutions such as SIEMs, EDR, IDS, etc. For example, a new ticket/case can automatically get opened and populated with alert details if a specific alert is triggered on the SIEM. 

Incident resolution time is a vital indication of SOC performance. To minimize incident resolution time, many ticketing systems started to employ machine learning to speed things up and reduce manual work, making the response process more efficient. Reporting is a core component of ticketing systems. Thus, most ticketing systems can export reports in different formats. 

A powerful incident management platform is "Request Tracker," particularly the "Request Tracker For Incident Response" edition. 

Figure - zoom in


According to the Request Tracker developers:

"Request Tracker for Incident Response (RTIR) builds on all the features of RT and provides pre-configured queues and workflows designed for incident response teams. It's the tool of choice for many CERT and CSIRT teams all over the globe." 

The incident management workflow of Request Tracker for Incident Response was developed by Janet CSIRT and Terena (now GANT). It is well explained in RTIR incident handling workflow document.
